&lt;p&gt;A review of paper from (Journal of Economics), published by Omer Tamuz's Group&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a title="DarwinPeacock, Maklaan, CC BY 3.0 &amp;lt;https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/3.0&amp;gt;, via Wikimedia Commons" href="https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Social_Network_Diagram_(segment).svg"&gt;&lt;img width="512" alt="Social Network Diagram (segment)" src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e4/Social_Network_Diagram_%28segment%29.svg/512px-Social_Network_Diagram_%28segment%29.svg.png"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In brief, this paper&lt;sup id="fnref:1"&gt;&lt;a class="footnote-ref" href="https://jeanbourgain8.github.io/posts/Substack/Proof/Economics/asymptotic-sequential-learning/#fn:1"&gt;1&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/sup&gt; tries to focus on the convergance rate and its dependencies on actions and signals. They try to prove that the convergence occurs quickly with respect to signals' &lt;em&gt;external observations&lt;/em&gt; rather than actions using a two state stochastic process. Taking the case of Gaussian distribution as the signal distribution they prove that the convergence with respect to actions occurs by $(\sqrt{\log t})$ times faster. They also discuss the definitivity of the convergence placing an emphasis on the sublinerity of the actions' influence. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Note:&lt;/strong&gt; Sublinearity means $(\lim\limits_{n \to \infty} \frac{x_n}{n})$&lt;/p&gt;
